</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usaliciaswiftfoot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Salicia Swiftfoot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>DAOC Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/7/01 1:01:09 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.divineguildpics.homestead.com/files/SalSide.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Alt-tab (background) functionality restored</span><hr size=1> Developer on Alt Tabbing - there's more, let me keep digging.<br>
<br>
<br>
<B>Folks, <br>
<br>
Just wanted to give some insight into why our current "alt-tab policy" is the way it is. (Since some recent comments regarding this issue were not-quite-as-correct-as-they-could-have-been... <sigh> I blame myself.) <br>
<br>
Point 1: Why we kick you out of the game when you task-switch. <br>
<br>
You're running a pretty hefty application here. DAoC wants the full attention of your CPU and it wants all the VRAM/RAM it can get; in short, it wants "focus". If *any* other application takes that focus, DAoC's game-state is going to shut down - that's not going to change. You really shouldn't be running any other applications when you run DAoC (if you want the best performance), and you should disable anything that might popup a window in the middle of your gaming session. <br>
<br>
Point 2: Why we don't just disable alt-tab. <br>
<br>
Disabling alt-tab is "bad Windows programming". If any of you are on the Microsoft DirectX Developer's list you know what happens when anyone asks about disabling alt-tab. The poor sap is attacked by a pack of rabid wolves! Microsoft doesn't want Windows developers to disable task-switching. So we didn't. We further acknowledge the fact that it's your computer and you can do what you want with it (including task-switching). If you want to switch to another task, by all means do so, just not while you're sitting in our game taking up our server's cycles and bandwidth that other, more active players could put to better use. <br>
<br>
Point 3: We know this doesn't *prevent* hacking. <br>
<br>
We know that no software is hack-proof. However, we do what we can to slow the hackers down and to discourage "casual" hacking. Specific to this issue, we do hope that the game-state shutdown method will make things somewhat more difficult for the hackers. However, our focus is not to prevent all hacks on the client anyway. Instead, as we see the need, we will be adding/changing the client code so that we can monitor and detect the hacks and thereby the hackers. As a gentle reminder, hacking the client in any way is a one way ticket to the following (from the DAoC Rules of Conduct): <br>
<br>
[ PLAYER MAY NOT USE THE DAoC SERVICES TO: ] Use any game hacking/altering/cheating software or tools. Use of these types of programs will result in immediate termination of the Account and may subject you to civil and/or criminal liability. <br>
<br>
Marty </B> <p><a href = http://pub33.ezboard.com/bdaocdivine><img src=http://www.divineguildpics.homestead.com/files/SalDAoCSig.gif border=0></a><br><br>DAoC Moderator for <a href=http://thedruidsgrove.org/>The Druids Grove</a></B><br>Click <a href="http://divineguildpics.homestead.com/Memorial.html"> here</a> to read the last EQ story of Salicia Swiftfoot.<BR>
